# LinkedIn Cron Scheduler — crontab example
# Runs linkedin-cron.sh at 6:00 PM America/Denver (MST/MDT) every day.
#
# Option 1: Use CRON_TZ (recommended — supported by systemd timers & most modern cron)
# This automatically adjusts for DST (MST in winter, MDT in summer).
CRON_TZ=America/Denver
0 18 * * * /path/to/scripts/linkedin-cron.sh >> /path/to/logs/linkedin-cron-crontab.log 2>&1

# Option 2: If CRON_TZ is not supported (legacy vixie cron), use two UTC entries
# to cover both MST (UTC-7) and MDT (UTC-6) and rely on the script's
# idempotency lock to skip the redundant run.
#
# 6:00 PM MST = 01:00 UTC (next day) — active Nov–Mar
# 6:00 PM MDT = 00:00 UTC (next day) — active Mar–Nov
# 0 0 * * * /path/to/scripts/linkedin-cron.sh >> /path/to/logs/linkedin-cron-crontab.log 2>&1
# 0 1 * * * /path/to/scripts/linkedin-cron.sh >> /path/to/logs/linkedin-cron-crontab.log 2>&1

# Option 3: systemd timer (see docs/linkedin-cron-setup.md for full unit files)
# [Timer]
# OnCalendar=*-*-* 18:00:00 America/Denver
# Persistent=true
